<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-27T12:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-27T12:36:00-05:00" n="240" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 818.00/34T</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Limon</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-27T12:00:00-05:36">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 27, 1918, noon.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Gomez and Mariano Guardia, Minister of Finance under Gonzalez, and 60
                                men forced to surrender at Turrialba by placing in front of
                                Government lines two daughters of Guardia. This stratagem boasted of
                                by Tinoco commander, a cousin. Movement practically over. Am
                                encouraging ex-President Duran and members of Central American Court
                                of Justice to urge strongly retirement of Tinoco. Attitude of latter
                                is one of defiance of the United States. He has stated repeatedly
                                that for the honor of the country he will not get out at the
                                suggestion of foreign government, when real reason is simply desire
                                for office and graft, and doubtful as ever that he will voluntarily
                                resign. Treatment to be given rebels still in doubt. …</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>